<HEADLINE>
<P>
CULINARY SOS: CHEESE-CHIVE BISCUITS, OATMEAL COOKIES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ROSE DOSTI 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 DEAR SOS: The Beef Barron Restaurant at the Flamingo Hilton Hotel in Laughlin, 
Nev., serves the most delicious cheese-and-chive biscuits I have ever eaten. 
Any possibility of getting the recipe? I'm sure your readers would enjoy them 
too. 
</P>
<P>
 -- CELIA 
</P>
<P>
 DEAR CELIA: The biscuits are served with entrees at the restaurant, and more 
than a few readers have requested the recipe. CHEESE-CHIVE BISCUITS 
</P>
<P>
 1/4 cup oil 
</P>
<P>
 1 cup buttermilk 
</P>
<P>
 1 cup grated Cheddar cheese 
</P>
<P>
 1/4 cup sliced green onions or chives 
</P>
<P>
 1 1/2 cups cake flour 
</P>
<P>
 1/2 cup bread flour 
</P>
<P>
 1 teaspoon salt 
</P>
<P>
 1 tablespoon sugar 
</P>
<P>
 1 tablespoon baking powder 
</P>
<P>
 1 teaspoon ground black pepper 
</P>
<P>
 1 teaspoon garlic power 
</P>
<P>
 Combine oil and buttermilk in large mixing bowl. Add cheese and green onions. 
Combine cake and bread flours, salt, sugar, baking powder, pepper and garlic 
powder in separate bowl. Gradually add to liquid ingredients, folding in until 
batter is well incorporated but not overmixed. 
</P>
<P>
 On floured board, roll dough out to 1- to 1 1/4-inch thickness. Cut into 
desired shapes, such as rounds or squares. Place on baking sheets, or place in 
greased cupcake tins for individual biscuits. Bake at 300 degrees 10 to 15 
minutes or until slightly browned. Do not over-bake. Makes 1 dozen biscuits. 
</P>
<P>
 Each biscuit contains about: 
</P>
<P>
 162 calories; 383 mg sodium; 11 mg cholesterol; 8 grams fat; 17 grams 
carbohydrates; 5 grams protein; 0.07 gram fiber. 
</P>
<P>
 DEAR SOS: Because of the January earthquake, I've lost my recipe for 
Disneyland's oatmeal cookies. Help! 
</P>
<P>
 -- LILA 
</P>
<P>
 DEAR LILA: Ask, and you shall have it back. WALT DISNEY'S OATMEAL COOKIES 
</P>
<P>
 2 cups flour 
</P>
<P>
 1/2 teaspoon salt 
</P>
<P>
 1/2 teaspoon baking soda 
</P>
<P>
 1 teaspoon baking powder 
</P>
<P>
 3/4 teaspoon ground cinnamon 
</P>
<P>
 1 1/3 cups butter 
</P>
<P>
 1 1/4 cups granulated sugar 
</P>
<P>
 3/4 cup brown sugar, packed 
</P>
<P>
 2 large eggs 
</P>
<P>
 2 tablespoons water 
</P>
<P>
 1/2 teaspoon vanilla 
</P>
<P>
 2 1/2 cups uncooked rolled oats (not instant) 
</P>
<P>
 1 1/4 cups raisins 
</P>
<P>
 Combine flour, salt, baking soda, baking powder and cinnamon in medium bowl. 
Set aside. 
</P>
<P>
 Cream butter in very large bowl. Beat in granulated and brown sugars. Beat in 
eggs, 1 at time. Add water and vanilla. Mix until well blended, about 4 
minutes. 
</P>
<P>
 Mix oats, raisins and flour mixture into sugar mixture. Stir until thoroughly 
blended. Drop by large tablespoons onto ungreased baking sheet. Bake at 350 
degrees 9 to 14 minutes, or until light-brown in color. Cool on baking sheet 
before removing from pan. Makes 4 dozen. 
</P>
<P>
 Each cookie contains about: 
</P>
<P>
 128 calories; 90 mg sodium; 23 mg cholesterol; 6 grams fat; 18 grams 
carbohydrates; 2 grams protein; 0.12 grams fiber. 
</P>
<P>
 Only recipes of general interest will be printed. Send recipe request to 
Culinary SOS, Food Section, The Times, Times Mirror Square, Los Angeles 90053. 
Include restaurant address when requesting recipes from restaurants. We are 
unable to answer recipe requests by mail.  
</P>
