COMMUNITY NEWS: HAWTHORNE; POOL HALL OWNER SUES TO GET LIQUOR PERMIT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SCOTT SANDELL 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The owner of a billiards parlor has sued Hawthorne and the City Council in a 
bid to get a liquor permit. 
</P>
<P>
 Jerry Jamgotchian, owner of South Bay Billiards, filed suit in Los Angeles 
Superior Court Tuesday asking a judge to force the city to issue him a permit, 
which would let him apply for a state liquor license.He is also seeking 
$100,000 in legal fees and estimated lost revenue. 
</P>
<P>
 Jamgotchian's action comes nearly two months after the City Council denied him 
a liquor permit for his El Segundo Boulevard business. Council members said the 
pool hall is unsuitable for alcohol sales because it is near Hawthorne High 
School. 
</P>
<P>
 "I've been fighting to get this permit for five years," Jamgotchian said. "All 
my competitors in the billiards business can serve alcohol, but I can't." 
</P>
<P>
 But Councilwoman Martha Bails said other pool halls "may serve liquor, but 
they're not next door to a school." SCOTT SANDELL 
</P>
