<HEADLINE>
<P>
BY DESIGN; THE MORE UNGLAMOROUS, THE BETTER? 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LAURIE DRAKE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Sometimes the best disguise is no disguise -- hence the popularity of 
sunglasses and baseball caps, brim forward. 
</P>
<P>
 "Between those two accessories," says photographer Kathy Hutchins, "you've 
covered up half the face.The hair is hidden, too." 
</P>
<P>
 The third element in this equation is dull, shapeless clothing, all the better 
to hide a star body. Julia Roberts was recently spotted in Century City looking 
like any other mall girl, in a loose brown dress, big cardigan, bare legs and 
flats. 
</P>
<P>
 Think about it, says the Star's Janet Charlton: "Some actresses are so cute 
they don't dare get dolled up in their normal lives. They have to play their 
looks down if they want to go to the supermarket. Otherwise, men will still 
flirt with them, even if they don't know who they are. That's why sweat suits 
are so popular." 
</P>
<P>
 At the airport, if you see a sloppily dressed person walking with a man in a 
suit, "take a better look," photographer Vinnie Zuffante says. "That could be a 
celebrity and a chauffeur." LAURIE DRAKE 
</P>
</TEXT>
