<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS: PALOS VERDES PENINSULA; DEPUTY ASSIGNED TO MOTORCYCLE PATROL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SUSAN WOODWARD 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department has assigned a motorcycle patrol 
to the Palos Verdes Peninsula for the first time. 
</P>
<P>
 Deputy Andrew Parrott of the Lomita sheriff's station patrols in Rancho Palos 
Verdes, Rolling Hills and Rolling Hills Estates during the day Monday through 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
 Palos Verdes Estates has its own Police Department. 
</P>
<P>
 Traffic Sgt. Thomas Thomas said although accident rates on the peninsula have 
decreased for three years, the cities requested a motorcycle patrol to cut down 
on response time. 
</P>
<P>
 "If there's an accident, the road's basically shut down until it's cleaned up, 
and if (the officer is) in a regular car, he's stuck in traffic like everybody 
else," Thomas said. 
</P>
<P>
 The patrol will continue for at least a year, he said. SUSAN WOODWARD 
</P>
</TEXT>
